Analysis

This analysis shows the my vehicle purchase cost per mile by comparing the price and mileage when I purchased to the price and mileage when I plan to sell.

Scatterplot

car.lm <- lm(Price ~ Mileage, data=cardata)
boxCox(car.lm)

\(\lambda\) is close to 0.5, so I will use y transformation.

pink dashline = Prediction line for the car linear regression. blue dash line = Prediction line for the y-transformed car linear regression.

Conclusion

This linear regression shows that the slope is significant(p = 0.0006527). Hence the relationship is meaningful. My prediction for the model is $3850.55 after drove 60000 miles more than when I purchased. I bought the car $3000 with 120000 miles on it. I did not loss money by selling it, actually I got an $850.55 benefit. I am not consdinering gas, insurance, or any expenses while using car. Just care about price when I purchased the car and selling the car. The mean of the price of Nissan sentra is $15432.

Assumption

It is questionavle whether or not the above analysis is fully appropriate because of the lack of normality of the residuals shown in the Normal Q-Q plot and ResidualVS Order plot. Residuals VS Order plot has a pattern that shows error terms might appear to be correlated. However, in residuals versus fitted values plot, there are no real concerns with linearity because it doesn’t have any patterns. The linear regression model is arguable after checking appropriateness of model but we will still use model for the analysis at least most important assumption(Residuals versus fitted value plot) is met. And the vertical variation in the residuals seems constant enough for all fitted-values to assume constant variance of the errors.

car.lm <- lm(Price ~ Mileage, data=cardata)
par(mfrow=c(1,3))
plot(car.lm, which=1)
qqPlot(car.lm$residuals)
## [1] 19  9
plot(car.lm$residual, main="Residuals vs Order")
